INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'To Prepare the Daikon Radish:');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'With the knife, remove the sharp edges of the daikon slices to smooth them out. This technique is called "mentori." The rounded corners and edges will prevent the daikon from breaking and protect its shape. Next, score a cross on one flat side of the daikon slices, about ¼ inch deep, so they will absorb more flavors.');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, '');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'If you are going to serve rice with the oden, reserve the cloudy water from rinsing the rice. Fill a medium pot with this cold, cloudy water. Add the daikon to the pot. Turn on the stove to medium heat and cook, uncovered, for about 20 minutes. Drain and rinse the daikon in running water. Set aside. Tip: This method helps get rid of the daikon''s bitterness and odor and makes the daikon a beautiful white color. Make sure to cook the daikon starting with cold water. This allows the center of the daikon to cook slowly before the water reaches a boil and that will help cook the daikon evenly.');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, '');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'To Prepare the Konnyaku');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'Bring a small saucepan of water to a boil. Meanwhile, score one side of the konnyaku in a crisscross pattern: Make diagonal cuts in one direction about ⅛ inch (3 mm) deep and ⅛ inch (3 mm) apart, then repeat the diagonal cuts in the other direction. This will help the konnyaku absorb more flavors.');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'Next, cut the konnyaku into thirds crosswise. Then, cut each third in half diagonally, creating a triangle shape.');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, '');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'Place the konnyaku in the boiling water, cook for 3 minutes, and drain. Tip: This helps to remove the odor from the konnyaku.');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, '');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'To Remove the Excess Oil from the Oden Set');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'Put water in a donabe (Japanese clay pot) or a large, shallow pot and bring it to a boil. Add the oden set (Japanese fish cakes and fish balls—we call them nerimono) to the boiling water for 15-30 seconds. Tip: This recommended step removes the excess deep-frying oil from factory processing.');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, '');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'Remove the fish cakes and fish balls from the boiling water and transfer them to a plate or tray. Let cool. Keep the boiling water in the pot, if you are going to make mochi kinchaku. Otherwise, drain the water and rinse the pot.');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, '');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'To Make the Mochi Kinchaku (optional)');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'Blanch the aburaage (deep-fried tofu pouches) in the reserved boiling water for 15-30 seconds to remove the excess oil. Remove them from the water and set aside. Drain the water and rinse the pot.');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'Cut the aburaage in half crosswise to make two square pockets. Cut the kirimochi (rice cakes) in half or small enough to fit into the tofu pocket.');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'Open one aburaage pocket and put a piece of kirimochi inside. Use a toothpick to close the aburaage pouch so the mochi doesn''t fall out during cooking. Repeat to make the remaining pouches.');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'To Prepare the Broth');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'To the rinsed donabe or large pot, add the dashi (Japanese soup stock) and the rest of the seasonings for the oden broth. Mix well together.');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'To Cook the Oden');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'Put the daikon, konnyaku, and peeled boiled eggs in the donabe (or pot) and bring it to a boil.');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'Once boiling, reduce the heat to low or medium low to maintain a simmer. Cook, uncovered, for 20 minutes.');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'Meanwhile, cut the big pieces of fish cakes in the oden set in half or quarters so they are a convenient size to pick up with chopsticks. Here, I cut the larger Satsuma age (round fried fish cakes) into quarters and the chikuwa (baked fish cakes) diagonally in half.');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'I cut the gobo-maki (burdock fish cake rolls) and fish balls in half.');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'I cut the medium-sized Satsuma age in half. I cut the block of atsuage (thick, deep-fried tofu cutlet) in half crosswise and then cut each piece in half again diagonally.');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'For the small fish balls, you can thread two pieces onto a skewer to keep them together. Diagonally cut the hanpen (soft white fish cake) in quarters.');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'After 20 minutes, check your oden pot. If there''s so much broth that your oden pot will overflow when you add the oden set and other fish cakes, transfer some broth to a measuring cup (or bowl) and set aside. You can add this reserved broth to the pot later, as needed.');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'Now, add the oden set, other fish cakes, and dried knotted kombu to the pot and cook for 10 minutes.');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'After 10 minutes, add the hanpen (and the optional mochi kinchaku). Cook for 3 minutes. Now, your oden is ready to serve.');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'To Serve');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'Serve hot. Oden is usually served with a little bit of karashi (hot mustard) on the side. To make karashi, combine 2 tsp of karashi powder with 3 tsp (1 Tbsp) of hot water in a small bowl.');
INSERT INTO preparationSteps (recipe_id, step) VALUES (1605, 'Mix together, cover the bowl with plastic wrap, and flip upside down to let it steam under the bowl for 5 minutes to get a good taste and aroma. Unwrap the bowl and the karashi is ready to use.');
INSERT INTO recipes (id, name, source, preptime, waittime, cooktime, servings, comments, calories, fat, satfat, carbs, fiber, sugar, protein, instructions) VALUES (1606, 'Seared tilapia and lemon-caper sauce', 'Blue Apron', 600, 0, 1500, 2, '', 1044, 48, 20, 98, 8, 14, 62, 'Fill a medium pot with salted water; cover and heat to boiling on high. Add the **pasta** to the pot of boiling water and cook, uncovered, 7 to 9 minutes, or until tender. Turn off the heat. Drain thoroughly and return to the pot.
